<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>Written evidence submitted by Publish What You Pay (PWYP)</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:right"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:20pt">EIS 19</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Written evidence submitted by Publish What You Pay (PWYP)</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">About this submission</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This submission </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">comes from UK members of the Publish What You Pay  (PWYP) civil society coalition (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">www.publishwhatyoupay.org</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">a global network of over 700 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">civil society organisations across more than 50 countries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK coalition members are: ABColombia, Action Aid, Amnesty International UK, Burma Campaign, CAFOD, Campaign Against Arms Trade, CARE International UK, Christian Aid, Ecumenical Council for Corporat</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e Responsibility, Engineers Against Poverty, Global Poverty Project, Global Witness, ONE, Open Knowledge Foundation, Open Society Foundations, Oxfam Great Britain, Revenue Watch Institute, Save the Children UK, Scottish Catholic International Aid Fund, Tea</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rfund, Transparency International UK, United Nations Association of the UK, and World Vision International.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PWYP </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">members are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">united in their call for oil, gas and mining revenues to form the basis for development and improve the lives of women, youth and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">men in resource-rich countries. W</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> welcom</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the opportunity to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">provide this submission to the Committee and respond </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to questions most relevant to PWYP’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mandate </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as a coalition working for transparency and accountability in the extractive industries.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Th</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> sub</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mission was drafted by PWYP UK’s Coordinator</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Miles Litvinoff</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mlitvinoff@pwypuk.org), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">circulated among PWYP UK members for comment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">revised in light of comments received.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Executive summary</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> and recommendations</span></p><ul type="disc" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he economic contribution of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EI</span><a name="_ftnref1"></a><a href="#_ftn1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">globally </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">often </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">less </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">positive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> than it should be</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and in the long term this may impact negatively on their </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contribution to the UK economy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">P</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rofits </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in resource-rich developing countries in particular </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are excessively privatised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">unequal </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contractual t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">erms, profit shifting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transfer mispricing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">secretive deals, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and the use of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">anonymous </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">shell companies and tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ecrecy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">j</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">urisdictions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">havens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) to evade and avoid tax</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EI are associated in resource-rich developing countries with corruption and other aspects of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">widely documented </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">“resource curse”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (or better: “resource challenge”)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, including negative long-term social and environmental impacts</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Corporate governance conce</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rns about UK-listed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and UK-registered </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EI companies, a sense of injustice on the part of citizens of resource-rich developing countries, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reputational risks for the UK and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK financial institutions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will remain significant and in some cases high for a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s long as the EI lack transparency and accountability and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">do not visibly contribute to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">equitable and sustainable patterns of economic development.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There has not been sufficient constructive engagement between UK EI companies and NGOs.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PWYP has particular concerns about UK-listed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and UK-registered EI multinational companies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that belong to the American Petroleum Institute (API), have not dissociated themselves from the API</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> law suit in the US against the SEC’s rules for Dodd-Frank Sectio</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">n 1504 (country-by-country reporting of payments to governments), and may in some cases be lobbying to delay and/or weaken UK and EU implementation of the Accounting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Directive (Chapter 10: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">country-by-country reporting of payments to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">governments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Tr</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ansparency Directive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, such as by pleading the need for specific country </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">exemptions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Having called for the UK to sign up to the EITI for some years, PWYP sees UK EITI membership as a positive step.</span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK needs to implement the EITI to a high standard. </span></li><li style="font-family:Symbol; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 10.52pt; padding-left:7.48pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Pro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">mpt, comprehensive and effective implementation of the Accounting and Transparency Directives, can and should improve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK as a centre of excellence for best practice and corporate governance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></li></ul><p style="margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 18pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Recommenda</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ions </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should implement an open public registry of beneficial ownership for all UK-listed and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">registered companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and with other countries take speedy and effective action to curtail profit shifting and the use of tax secrecy jurisdictions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">havens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">– inc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">luding among them UK Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies – and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">publi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cation of all EI contracts and licences. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK Government should ensure s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">peedy and effective implementation of the EU Accounting and Transparency Directives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and as soon as possible implement the Directives with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">open and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">machine-readable data according to the G8 Open Data Charter.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">I financial transparency in the UK and EU needs to be accompanied by the establishment of a global mandatory EI financial transpa</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">rency standard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, i.e. equivalent disclosure rules in all major jurisdictions and capital markets.</span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK Government should make it clear to EI companies that a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">global mandatory transparency standard, without </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">any country </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">exemptions, is here to stay</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and that</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will not consider </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">company </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">special pleading</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> on alleged competition, confidentiality, cost or other grounds</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In the UK EITI process, the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pilot the EITI‘s recommendation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">public beneficial ownership transparency; ensure full EI contract </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transparency in the UK; support capacity-building efforts with civil society</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">;</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and as soon as possible implement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reporting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">open and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">machine-readable data. </span></li><li style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.11pt; padding-left:3.89pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK’s enforcement regime under Article 51 of the Accounting Directive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">needs to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be seen to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">effective and have adequate resourcing to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">detect and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">prevent misreporting.</span></li></ol><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What is the contribution to the UK economy of extractive industries in the UK? </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">PWYP is concerned that the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">economic </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">contribution of EI</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in the UK and other countries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">is </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">not as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">positive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as it </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sh</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ould be. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Globally, corruption and other aspects of the widely documented “resource curse”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(or better: “resource challenge)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">economic “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">externalities</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> are reco</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">gnised </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">wide-scale </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and largely socialised</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in terms of costs</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, i.e. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">costs are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">borne by society at large including in the UK.</span><a name="_ftnref2"></a><a href="#_ftn2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">By contrast, EI profits are excessively privatised, including through </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">exploitative contractual terms with some host countries (which ultimately impact on the UK through the effects of global </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">poverty and poor resource governance), </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the use of profit shifting through transfer mispricing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, secret deals,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the use of secretive shell companies and tax havens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> – the latter including UK Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.2  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he world’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">en </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">largest extractive companies, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">London</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-listed BP, Shell, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Glencore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Xstrata, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Rio Tinto, BHP</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Billiton</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Anglo American</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, are reported as </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">own</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing and controlling more than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">6,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">000</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> separate companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, at least a third of which are </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">incorporated in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ecrecy </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">j</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">urisdictions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (tax havens)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref3"></a><a href="#_ftn3">[3]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">: To address concerns about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">profit shifting, transfer mispricing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, secret deals</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the use of secretive shell companies and tax havens, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Government </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should implement an open public registry of beneficial ownership for all UK-listed and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">registered companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and with other countries take speedy and effective action to curtail profit shifting and the use of tax secrecy jurisdictions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(tax </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">havens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">) </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">– inc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">luding among them UK Overseas Territories and Crown Dependencies – and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">publi</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cation of all EI contracts and licences</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref4"></a><a href="#_ftn4">[4]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What are the corporate governance concerns raised by the number of extractive industries companies listed in the UK? Are there </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">reputational risks for the UK and UK financial institutions in being a centre for such businesses?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.1  Besides the “externalities” referred to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.1, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">which include negative environmental and human rights impacts, EI are associated</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in resource-rich developing countries </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with corruption</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">capital flight </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">similar </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">aspects of the “resource curse”</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (“resource challenge”)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, which across all economic sectors </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cost Africa an </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">estimated $854bn from 1970 to 2008.</span><a name="_ftnref5"></a><a href="#_ftn5">[5]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.2  Corporate governance co</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ncerns about EI companies listed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and registered </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in the UK</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reputational risks for the UK and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK financial institutions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">are considerable and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">will remain </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">significant and in some cases high </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as long as the EI globally exhibit a lack of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">transparency and accountability</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and do not visibly contribute to equitable and sustainable patterns of economic development.</span><a name="_ftnref6"></a><a href="#_ftn6">[6]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">An estimated </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.6 billion people</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> live in resource-rich developing countries, of whom at present approximately </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">640m or 40%</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> li</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ve </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ess than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">$2 a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">day</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> (a higher proportion than </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in resource</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">poor countries</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, while EI senior executives earn </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">far more than is reasonable</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><a name="_ftnref7"></a><a href="#_ftn7">[7]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.3  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK-listed EI companies and UK financial institutions will </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">therefore </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be associated with a sense of injustice on the part of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">hundreds of thousands of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">citizens of resource-rich developing countries unless and until UK-listed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">/registered </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">companies are clearly </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and comprehensively proven </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to be contributing</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">equitabl</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and sustainab</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">l</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to host-country economies through payment of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">appropriate levels of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">taxes, royalties, etc.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, for the non-renewable natural resource they extract. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">2.4  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK Government should ensure s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">peedy and effective implementation of the EU Accounting </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Directive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">(Chapter 10: </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">country-by-country reporting of payments to governments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">)</span><a name="_ftnref8"></a><a href="#_ftn8">[8]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Transparency Directive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and as soon as possible implement the Directives with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">open and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">machine-readable data ac</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">cording to the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">G8 </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Open Data Charter.</span><a name="_ftnref9"></a><a href="#_ftn9">[9]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In addition, EI financial transparency in the UK and EU needs to be accompanied by the establishment of a global mandatory EI financial transparency standard</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, i.e. equivalent disclosure rules in all major jurisdictions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and capital markets, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and to lead to effective EI financial accountability, including </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">regarding company </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">beneficial ownership and contract transparency as noted in </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">para </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">1.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> above, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">empowered and informed civil society in resource-rich developing countri</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">es able to hold companies and their governments to account for natural resource revenues. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Is there sufficient engagement between UK extractive industries and the NGO sector? Are there examples of best practice in engagement between the extractive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">industries and NGOs?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.1  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">To date there has not been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">sufficient constructive </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">engagement between UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">companies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and NGO</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">In PWYP’s experience, EI companies have engag</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">only </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">very reluctantly in initiatives that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enhance transparency and accountability, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">often alleging </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">– but failing to satisfactorily substantiate – cost, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">confidentiality, competitiveness and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">supposed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">criminal liability as reasons why they cannot become more transparent and accountable. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.2  However, there have been differences between min</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ing and oil companies in this regard, and among oil companies. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Among the larger companies, m</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">in</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ers</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> have </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">appeared </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">more willing to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recognise and implement the emerging global mandatory transparency standard </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">than have oil companies, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">although </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">among UK oil companies one smaller company has </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">already </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">embrace</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> financial transparency on a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proactive and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">voluntary basis. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.3  PWYP has concerns about the fact that </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK-listed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and UK-registered EI multinational companies </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that belong to the American Petro</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">leum Institute (API) have not dissociated themselves from</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, and therefore can be considered to support,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the API</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> law suit in the US </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">against the SEC’s rules for Dodd-Frank Section 1504 (country-by-country reporting of payments to governments</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, equivalent to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the EU Directives’ requirements).</span><a name="_ftnref10"></a><a href="#_ftn10">[10]</a></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.4  S</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ome </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EI companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">have been </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">lobbying to delay and/or weaken UK and EU implementation of the Accounting and Transparency Directive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s, such as by pleading the need for specific country </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">exemptions</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and/or alleging compet</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">itiveness concerns in light of delays in US implementation of Dodd-Frank Section 1504 following the API court case, which the companies themselves instigated. All this despite the UK Government’s and the G8’s public commitment to see these Directives speed</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ily and fully implemented.</span><a name="_ftnref11"></a><a href="#_ftn11">[11]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> PWYP regards this as a lack of good faith on the part of such companies, which claim to champion transparency and to obey the law wherever they operate.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">3.5  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Recommendation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">: The UK Government should make it clear to EI companie</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s that a </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">global mandatory transparency standard, without </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">any country </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reporting exemptions, is here to stay and that it will not </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">consider special pleading </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">on the part of EI companies on alleged competition, confidentiality, cost or other grounds</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">What </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">is the impact o</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> the industry of the UK signing up to the EITI?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.1  PWYP has called for the UK to sign up to the EITI for</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">some years and sees this as a positive step. As </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the initiator of the EITI, the UK’s commitment </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">to</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">implement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> helps address </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">objections</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">that the EITI has been yet another instance of the global North </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">telling</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the South what to do. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">It will also provide a forum in which </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">civil society can, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">potentially</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, dialogue constructively with industry and government.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.2  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">There is</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> need for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">UK EITI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">delivery to match the rhetoric</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> about the UK “getting its house in order”. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Although</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, unlike Norway, the UK failed to invest proceeds from its North Sea oil </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">bonanza</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in long-term </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">funding</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> for pensions </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">other public goods,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK needs a well-informed public</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> debate about </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">resource sustainability, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">progress towards a low-carbon economy</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and the entrenchment of transparency as a national norm.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.3  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">T</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">he UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">implement the EITI to a high standard. Anything less will reflect negatively on the UK’s reputation as</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> a champion of </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">good governance. </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.4</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ommen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">io</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:  The UK Government should ensure that the UK </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">pilot</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> the EITI‘s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">recommendation </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">for </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">beneficial ownership public transparency; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ensure </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">full EI contract transparency in the UK; </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">through the multi-stakeholder group </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">support “</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">capacity-building efforts, especially with civil society and through</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">civil society organisations, to increase awareness of the process, improve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">understanding of the information and data from the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">reports, and enc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">ourage</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">use of the information</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">”; and as soon as possible implement </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the EITI </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">with </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">open and </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">machine-readable data.</span><a name="_ftnref12"></a><a href="#_ftn12">[12]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">Would increased regulation for London listed extractives companies result in competition from elsewhere or can it be used to make the UK a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold"> centre of excellence for best practice and corporate governance?</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.1  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK should apply </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">proportionate</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and effective </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">regulation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to UK-listed </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and UK-registered </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">EI companies</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> irrespective of potential or alleged effects on </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">competition</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Attempting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> to benefit from anything resembling a “race to the bottom” </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">would</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> be a poor approach for the UK to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">take</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and undermine its </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">international</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> moral authority</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> in this area</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.2  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Prompt</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">comprehensive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">and effective </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">implementation</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Accounting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> and Transparenc</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">y </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Directives</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">as noted above, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">can and should </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">improve</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">the UK as a centre of excellence for best practice and corporate governance</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">5</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">.3  </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">Re</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">c</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">ommen</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">d</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">a</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">t</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">io</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; text-decoration:underline">n</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">:</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">The UK’s </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">enforcement</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> regime under Article 51 of the </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Accounting</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">Directive</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">needs to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">be seen to be </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">effective.</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">This requires adequate Government resourcing of scrutiny of company reports under the Directives and sufficient penalties to </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">deter </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">misreporting.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-style:italic">23 September 2013</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:12pt; font-weight:bold">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:11pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div><hr style="width:33%; height:1px; text-align:left" /><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn1"></a><a href="#_ftnref1">[1]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> “Extractive industries” are abbreviated to ”EI” throughout this submission.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn2"></a><a href="#_ftnref2">[2]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> US$ 2.15 trillion as the “cost of environmental damage caused by the world’s 3,000 largest publicly-listed companies in 2008” – UN </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Environment</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> Programme Finance Initiative and Principles for Responsible Investment, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Universal Ownership: Why Environmental E</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">xternalities Matter to Institutional Investors</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, 2010, http://www.unpri.org/viewer/?file=files/6728_ES_report_environmental_externalities.pdf, p.2.</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><a name="_ftn3"></a><a href="#_ftnref3">[3]</a><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt"> PWYP Norway, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Piping Profits</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, 2011, http://www.publishwhatyoupay.org/sites/publishwhatyoupay.org/files/FINAL</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">%20pp%20norway.pdf; see also </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">Christian Aid, </span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">Multinational Corporations and the Profit-Shifting Lure of Tax Havens</span><span style="font-family:Calibri; font-size:10pt">, 2013, http://www.c